			<td colspan="6" class="DetailTitle" style="text-align:center;">
                            Summary on Grant Application Form</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td colspan="6" class="DetailValue" style="padding:5px;">
                        <span id="lblAbstract">The proposed research will be a contribution to fluctuatuion theory for Levy processes, and will focus mainly on questions involving their local behaviour. It is well known that the theory of large-time behaviour of random walks is intimately connected to properties of the ladder height and ladder time processes, and exactly the same is true for Levy processes, both for large-time and small time behaviour. However, until the recent paper by Vigon, Levy process theory lacked one obvious tool, which is an analytic connection between the characteristics of the Levy process and the characteristics of its associated ladder height processes. In this work we will attempt to exploit this connection, which, Vigon has used to solve a longstanding problem about creeping of Levy processes, to problems of a similar nature. In the proposal we identify three such problems, involving creeping of the modulus, relative stability of the ladder height process, and the increase problem, but there are certainly others.We will also see what applications of this technique are possible in higher dimensions; one target here would be an analogue of Rogozin's criterion for regularity of a half-line</span>
                        </td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td colspan="6" class="DetailTitle" style="text-align:center;">
